==English==

===Etymology===

Compound of ''[[smoke]]'' + ''[[fall]]''.

===Noun===

'''smokefall'''

<!-- PLEASE SEE DISCUSSION PAGE ABOUT SOURCES AND UNCERTAINTIES -->
# The close of the day before [[nightfall]], when [[fog]] comes.
#: ''The moment in the draughty church at '''smokefall''''' - T.S. Eliot, "Burnt Norton" (1935 possible neologism)
# The [[soot]] [[fallout]] from a [[cloud]] of smoke.
#: ''The largest sea ice perturbations are generated by '''smokefall''' in spring.'' (1985 apparent neologism)
# An artificial [[waterfall]] of smoke for shows, a smoke fall.

